=> Definition

A Common Table Expression (CTE) is a temporary named result set defined using the WITH clause, which can be referenced within a SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE,
or DELETE statement.

WITH cte_name AS (
    SELECT ...
)
SELECT ...
FROM cte_name;
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
=> Why CTE is used

CTEs were introduced to improve query structure over subqueries.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
=> Limitations of subqueries:
Hard to read when nested
Difficult to debug
Cannot reuse logic easily
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
=> Advantages of CTE:
Improves readability
Breaks query into logical steps
Makes complex queries easier to manage
Supports multi-step transformations
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
=>Key Concept
CTE = preparation step
Main query = final result
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PRACTICE-QUESTIONS
1-- Find films whose rental_rate is higher than average

WITH avge_rent as (select AVG(rental_rate) as avg_rental
from film)
select title, rental_rate
from film
where rental_rate > (select avg_rental from  avge_rent);

=> Explanation:
The CTE calculates the average rental rate of all films and stores it as avg_value.
The main query retrieves film titles and rental rates where the rental rate is greater than the calculated average.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2=> -- Find customers who spent more than 200.
WITH total_amt AS (
SELECT customer_id, SUM(amount) AS spent_amt
FROM payment
GROUP BY customer_id
)
SELECT customer_id
FROM total_amt
WHERE spent_amt > 200;
=> Explanation:The CTE calculates total spending for each customer using SUM and GROUP BY.
The main query filters customers whose total spending exceeds 200.


3=> Customers Who Rented More Than 5 Times
WITH total_rentals AS (
SELECT customer_id, COUNT(rental_id) AS rented_count
FROM rental
GROUP BY customer_id
)
SELECT customer_id, rented_count
FROM total_rentals
WHERE rented_count > 5;

=> Explanation: The CTE counts the number of rentals for each customer.
The main query selects customers whose rental count is greater than five.

4: Top 5 Customers by Spending

WITH spent_amt AS (
SELECT customer_id, SUM(amount) AS spending_amt
FROM payment
GROUP BY customer_id
)
SELECT customer_id, spending_amt
FROM spent_amt
ORDER BY spending_amt DESC
LIMIT 5;

=>Explanation:
The CTE calculates total spending for each customer.
The main query orders the results in descending order of spending and returns the top five customers.
This query demonstrates ranking using ORDER BY and LIMIT.

=>5: Films with More Than 3 Copies in Inventory
WITH film_num AS (
    SELECT f.film_id, f.title, COUNT(i.inventory_id) AS film_count
    FROM film f
    JOIN inventory i ON f.film_id = i.film_id
    GROUP BY f.film_id, f.title
)
SELECT film_id, title, film_count
FROM film_num
WHERE film_count > 3;

=>Explanation:
The CTE joins the film and inventory tables and counts the number of inventory records for each film.
Each row in the inventory table represents one copy of a film.
The main query filters films that have more than three copies.

=>6: Customers Whose Spending Is Above Average

WITH customer_total AS (
SELECT customer_id, SUM(amount) AS total_spent
FROM payment
GROUP BY customer_id
),
avg_spending AS (
SELECT AVG(total_spent) AS avg_amt
FROM customer_total
)
SELECT customer_id, total_spent
FROM customer_total
WHERE total_spent > (
    SELECT avg_amt FROM avg_spending
);

=>Explanation:
The first CTE calculates total spending per customer.
The second CTE calculates the average of these totals.
The main query selects customers whose total spending exceeds the average.
This is an example of a multi-step query where one aggregation depends on another.

6. Key Concepts
A CTE behaves like a temporary table within a query
It allows separation of calculation and filtering logic
It is particularly useful for aggregation and multi-step queries
Multiple CTEs can be used for layered calculations
It improves readability and maintainability of SQL queries


----------------------Recursive CTE --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

A Recursive CTE is a type of Common Table Expression that references itself to repeatedly execute a query until a specified condition is met.

It is mainly used for:

generating sequences (numbers, dates)
working with hierarchical data (parent-child relationships)

Structure
A recursive CTE has two parts:
Base case – starting point
Recursive part – repeats the logic
Both parts are combined using UNION ALL.

Key Points
Uses WITH RECURSIVE
Must have a stopping condition
Runs repeatedly until the condition becomes false

Example Query

WITH RECURSIVE numbers AS (
SELECT 1 AS n   -- base case

    UNION ALL

    SELECT n + 1
    FROM numbers
    WHERE n < 5     -- stop condition
)
SELECT * FROM numbers;

Explanation
The query starts with 1 (base case)
Then it keeps adding 1 to the previous value
It repeats until n < 5 becomes false
Final output: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5















